Hi, In a project I am only interested in two errors.

1. unexpected EOF during the initial TLS connection setup(with rustls backend)
2. (when using openssl backend) Error code 5? (which is also basically the same thing as 1. i.e. connection reset during initial tls handshake)

Examples of these errors,

With rustls backend,

```rust
Custom {
    kind: Other,
    error: Custom {
        kind: UnexpectedEof,
        error: "tls handshake eof",
    },
}
```


With openssl backend,

```rust
Ssl(
    Error {
        code: ErrorCode(
            5,
        ),
        cause: None,
    },
    X509VerifyResult {
        code: 0,
        error: "ok",
    },
)
```

I understand I have to downcast these traits into structs to be able to read them but I just can't figure out how or what type to down cast it to?

The `Custom` struct in `rustls` error is a private struct in `std::io` so I can't downcast it to that and there is no way to read the error without it. 


The `Ssl` struct/object in `openssl` error is `openssl::ssl::Error`.

`reqwest` doesn't re-export `openssl` so I installed `openssl = 0.10.41` but down casting it to this type just yields `None`.

Then, Some one pointed out that `reqwest` uses `native-tls = 0.2.8` which uses, `openssl = 0.10.29` so I tried this version but it doesn't build anymore. 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7921368/184524655-9335c29f-621c-4151-8c43-40d4e4aa128d.png)


I am not sure if this is correct place to put this issue? I have tried my best to figure this out, also asked about it in some places and still no where close to solving this problem. It's just really frustrating and overly difficult to read the actual error. 


Example code, 

```rust
use std::error::Error;
use reqwest::Client;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), std::io::Error> {
    let client = Client::new();

    match client.get("https://google.com").send().await {
        Ok(v) => {
            println!("{:?}", v.status());

            println!("{:?}", v.text().await);
        }
        Err(e) => {
            if !e.is_connect() {
                return Ok(())
            }

            let herror = e.source().unwrap().downcast_ref::<hyper::Error>().unwrap();

            println!("{:?}", e.to_string());
            let serror = herror.source().unwrap();
            println!("{:#?} ", serror,);
        }
    }
    
    Ok(())
}
```

[Playground Link](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=32581dd91d30a3285db1e8c520baebe6)

This adds retry policies, somewhat kind of like redirect policies. This includes a new `ClientBuilder::retry()` method, and a `reqwest::retry` module to build a retry policy.

## Example

```rust
let retries = reqwest::retry::for_host("api.github.com")
    .classify_fn(|req_rep| {
        if req_rep.status() == Some(SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE) {
            req_rep.retryable()
        } else {
            req_rep.success()
       }
    })
```

Closes #316 
